doc.ContractDescription: WE WERE AWARDED AN 85-KS SUZAKU CATEGORY C OBSERVATION OF THE NUCLEUS OF THE NEARBY RADIO-LOUD AGN NGC 6251, IN AN EFFORT TO UNDERSTAND THE ACCRETION-FLOW STRUCTURE AND CIRCUMNUCLEAR OBSCURATION OF THIS PROTOTYPICAL LOW-EXCITATION RADIO GEOMETRY. OUR SPECIFIC GOAL OF THIS DEEP SUZAKU OBSERVATION IS TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT LOW-EXCITATION RADIO GALAXIES ARE POWERED BY ACCRETION OF HOT GAS FROM THEIR AMBIENT X-RAY ENVIRONMENTS, AS OPPOSED TO HIGH-EXCITATION RADIO GALAXIES, WHICH ACCRETE COLD GAS (HARDCASTLE, EVANS,&CROSTON 2007). OUR SUZAKU OBSERVATION THEREFORE PROVIDE NEW CONSTRAINTS ON SELF-CONSISTENT MODELS OF ACCRETION AND FEEDBACK IN RADIO-LOUD AGN. TO DATE, WE HAVE USED SUZAKU TO SEARCH FOR THE SIGNATURES OF COLD-GAS ACCRETION: PROMINENT AND POSSIBLY BROADENED FE KA LINES, NUCLEAR OBSCURATION FROM NEUTRAL MATERIAL, AND COMPTON REFLECTION AT ENERGIES>10 KEY. OUR ACCEPTED PAPER (EVANS ET AL. 2011, APJ, 741, L4) DEMONSTRATES CONCLUSIVELY THAT THERE ARE NO SIGNATURES OF OBSCURED, ACCRETIONRELATED X-RAY EMISSION IN NGC 6251, AND WE SHOWED THAT THE LUMINOSITY OF ANY SUCH COMPONENT MUST BE SUBSTANTIALLY SUB-EDDINGTON IN NATURE. OUR NEXT STEPS ARE TO FULLY CHARACTERIZE THE HOT-GAS ENVIRONMENT OFNGC 6251, BASED ON OUR PRELIMINARY WORK, WHICH SUGGESTS THAT THE AGN IS LIKELY TO DERIVE ITS POWER FROM THE ACCRETION OF THIS PHASE VIA THE BONDI MECHANISM. FURTHERMORE, NGC 6251 IS ALSO A HIGHLY VARIABLE SOURCE (BOTH ON INTRA- AND INTER-OBSERVATION TIMESCALES). WE PLAN TO USE OUR SUZAKU DATA TO EXPLORE THE TEMPORAL VARIABILITY OF THE AGN, IN CONCERT WITH MONITORING OBSERVATIONS USING THE VLA AND TEV TELESCOPES. WE ARE ALSO WORKING ON CHARACTERIZING SHOCK HEATING TO X-RAY ENERGIES IN THE KNOWN RADIO LOBE.
